Existing values use shared read-only access by default.

Binding an existing value to another name does not silently copy it.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    items ~= {"a", "b"}
    shared_items = items
]

### Contract

- Any number of shared accesses may coexist.
- Shared access is read-only.
- Shared access does not imply ownership transfer.
- The rule applies uniformly to stack and heap values.
- Beanstalk has no source `&` or `&mut` operators.
- A backend may optimize representation, but observable source semantics must stay the same.

Binding mutability is separate from access. A mutable binding can still be
shared read-only. An exclusive operation must satisfy the borrow rules before
it can proceed.

### Alias conflicts

A later use of a shared alias can prevent overlapping mutation:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    items ~= {"a", "b"}
    shared_items = items

    -- Invalid because shared_items is used again after the mutation.
    ~items.push("c") catch:
    ;

    io.line([: [shared_items.length()] items])
]

Use `copy` when the second name needs an independent value.
